        <h2 class="section-title">Why Consider These Languages?</h2>
        
        <div class="features-grid">
            <div class="feature-card">
                <div class="feature-icon">🧠</div>
                <h3 class="feature-title">New Perspectives</h3>
                <p>
                    Learning an underrated language often provides new ways of thinking about programming problems. Functional languages like Haskell or Elixir can reshape how you approach state management and concurrency.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="feature-card">
                <div class="feature-icon">🚀</div>
                <h3 class="feature-title">Performance Gains</h3>
                <p>
                    Many underrated languages like Crystal and Nim offer exceptional performance while maintaining programmer productivity with clean, high-level syntax.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="feature-card">
                <div class="feature-icon">🛠️</div>
                <h3 class="feature-title">Specialization</h3>
                <p>
                    Some languages excel in specific domains: Erlang for fault-tolerant systems, F# for financial modeling, or OCaml for building compilers and static analyzers.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="feature-card">
                <div class="feature-icon">👥</div>
                <h3 class="feature-title">Community</h3>
                <p>
                    Smaller language communities are often more welcoming, with greater opportunities to contribute and make an impact. You can become a recognized expert faster.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="feature-card">
                <div class="feature-icon">💼</div>
                <h3 class="feature-title">Career Differentiation</h3>
                <p>
                    While job listings may be fewer, specialists in underrated languages often command higher salaries and face less competition in their specific niches.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="feature-card">
                <div class="feature-icon">🔄</div>
                <h3 class="feature-title">Cross-Pollination</h3>
                <p>
                    Concepts from these languages are increasingly finding their way into mainstream ones. Learning them today gives you insight into the future of programming.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cta-section">
            <h2 class="cta-title">Ready to Explore Something New?</h2>
            <p class="cta-description">
                Expand your programming horizons by learning one of these underrated languages. You'll gain new skills, perspectives, and possibly find the perfect tool for your next project.
            </p>
            <div class="cta-buttons">
                <a href="#languages" class="btn btn-light">Browse Languages</a>
                <a href="#" class="btn" style="background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.2);">Resource List</a>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2 class="section-title" id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        
        <div class="faq-container">
            <div class="faq-item active">
                <div class="faq-question">
                    <span>Is it worth spending time learning an underrated language?</span>
                    <span class="faq-icon">▼</span>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <p>
                        Absolutely. While mainstream languages like Python and JavaScript offer abundant job opportunities, learning an underrated language can provide unique benefits: deeper programming insights, specialized problem-solving approaches, and sometimes a competitive advantage in niche markets. Many programmers report that learning languages like Haskell or Elixir improved their coding in other languages too.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-question">
                    <span>Which underrated language is easiest to learn for beginners?</span>
                    <span class="faq-icon">▼</span>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <p>
                        For beginners, languages with familiar syntax and good documentation are ideal. Crystal and Nim are relatively approachable with syntax inspired by Ruby and Python respectively. Elixir also offers excellent documentation and a welcoming community. If you're already familiar with C# or the .NET ecosystem, F# provides a gentle introduction to functional programming concepts.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-question">
                    <span>Can I get a job using these languages?</span>
                    <span class="faq-icon">▼</span>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <p>
                        Yes, but the job market is more specialized. Companies using these languages often choose them deliberately for their specific advantages, leading to focused, challenging roles. Elixir has a growing job market in web development, F# in finance and enterprise, Haskell in fintech, and Erlang in telecommunications and distributed systems. While you'll see fewer job listings, the positions often offer better compensation and interesting problems.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-question">
                    <span>Why aren't these languages more popular if they're so good?</span>
                    <span class="faq-icon">▼</span>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <p>
                        Language popularity depends on many factors beyond technical merit: historical timing, corporate backing, network effects, learning resources, and library ecosystems all play major roles. Many of these languages arrived after established players had already built large communities and ecosystems. Some, like Haskell and OCaml, prioritize mathematical elegance over approachability. Others, like Crystal and Nim, are still maturing their tooling and libraries.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-question">
                    <span>What resources are available for learning these languages?</span>
                    <span class="faq-icon">▼</span>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <p>
                        While underrated languages have fewer resources than mainstream ones, quality materials exist for all languages featured here. Most have excellent official documentation, active forums, and dedicated communities. Books are available for Elixir, Haskell, F#, and OCaml. Online courses exist for most of these languages, though sometimes in smaller numbers. GitHub repositories with example projects are also valuable learning resources.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

